column1: How many confirmed cases of COVID-19 will have been reported by the World Health Organization (WHO) for the United Kingdom as of 1 February 2021?
column5: ['Fewer than 3,000,000', 'Between 3,000,000 and 3,500,000, inclusive', 'More than 3,500,000 but fewer than 4,000,000', 'Between 4,000,000 and 4,500,000, inclusive', 'More than 4,500,000']
column6: ['Health']
The lockdown measures are working better than I anticipated - glad to be wrong.
WHO data and decreasing trend line over remaining days now makes this an empirical certainty.

I miscalculated how much of an effect the lockdowns in the UK would immediately have on the rates of infection. It really reduced the numbers from day-to-day and week-to-week. Adjusting my initial view of the numbers from 4 to 4.5M. to 3.5 to 4M. Good for them, hopefully the trend continues.
Trend has been closing on 20k a day, will unlikely be over 4M in 4 days from now (it will take more than a tripling of the number of cases to near it).

Total PCR tests reported for 25 January 2021 is 196,510. There are only two days after 06 September 2020 (192,892 PCR tests) with a lower number of PCR tests, namely 30 November 2020 (185,276 PCR tests) and 07 December 2020 (181,493 PCR tests).
It would require an average of about 55,000 cases/day through 2/1/21 to exceed 4 million cases at this point.

Cases continue trending down, leading to an expected 3.8M cases by the end of the month. At this point, it would take a far more aggressive surge in cases than is likely to occur for the total to exceed 4M. I'm maintaining a 1% chance that a data revision pushes the official number higher.

22,195 cases today. It seems the bad weather has closed various testing centres, and will have prevented many individuals accessing tests. Case positivity has stopped dropping, but we are at sufficiently low case numbers now. I expect a rise over the week as people can finally get to tests, but one back up to the 30,000 mark. One thing the snow will have done is keep people at home so I wouldn't expect a significant rise in cases from any ill-advised socialising over the weekend before 01/02/21

Clearly a shortage of PCR tests (262,111 PCR test; total tesing volume of 412,204 as of 24 January 2021), almost two out of five tests have been a " lateral flow device tests that give results in less than an hour, without needing to go to a laboratory". No wonder positive tests fall accordingly. The question remains if and when the real PCR test series will be picked up again before 31 January 2021.
Yesterday 3617463, 8 days to go, currently below 40K cases per day. Would need an average of 47900 to leave bin 3. Going all in for bin 3.

Currently on 3,617,463 cases on 24th January. Average daily new cases over the past week is at 37,156. To go over 4,000,000 cases by 1st Feb the average daily new cases would have to be 54,648, a 47% jump on current average daily rates. I don't see that happening while the UK remains in lockdown and cases are trending downwards, barring a change or anomaly in data reporting.
The recent cases/day average continues to remain below the approx. 46,000/day average that would (now) have to occur to exceed four million by 2/1/21. (https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb)

The UK just reached over 3.5M cases. With their new lockdown restrictions that went into effect on January 5th, coronavirus cases have steadily decreased. Given these restrictions and the current rate of about 200K cases per week, cases climbing another 500K in 10 days doesn't seem possible. https://www.ft.com/content/50b5563a-c025-44ce-a135-2eb13be96c07
3.5m just reached with 10 days to go. Rates at about 35k will get an additional 375k cases, so consider it very unlikely to get to 4m by Feb 1.

Back up to 40,261 cases for tomorrow. But, even with the 4 day rise from 33,400 to 40,300, the case positivity has barely moved all week (allowing for noise) after reducing since the start of 2021. It looks like we are entering the slower stages of recovery. Encouraging for the country, but those numbers will put the 01/02/21 total very close to the 4m mark. The 2% will be reduced next week if the case numbers drop along with the weekly drop in tests performed over the weekend.

Further number of cases falling with recent average now less than 40k cases so 3.5-4m very likely now but doesn't take a huge increase to start creeping up to over 4m so still leaving a chance of that but that window is rapidly vanishing.

1/21/21: The most recent 5-day cases/day average is 37,947/day. (1/17/21 thru 1/21/21.) If this average is roughly maintained total cases should come in below 4,000,000 by 2/1/21. (..Assuming there are now 11 days left in this question it will take an average of about 45,000 cases per day through 2/1 to exceed the 4 million number.) (https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb)
Today: 3,505,758 Since my last forecast, daily new cases: <40,000

Updating forecast upwards for 3.5-4 based on further drop in latest daily figures but I share @greenbankse's concerns about lack of representation in the test figures. Hard to see what will change significantly over the next 10 days though.

For the decline in new daily cases to be reversed, there would need to be a cause and then a week for cases to rise. There have been no such events/causes reported, which would make less than 4 mln very close to certain.

37,892 cases to be reported tomorrow. I would reduce the 2% but it is 10 days out and I am concerned about a lack of representation. A new report from Imperial College London has raised questions about whether the lockdown is actually doing anything (https://spiral.imperial.ac.uk/bitstream/10044/1/85583/2/REACT1_r8a_final.pdf). Test positivity is going down, but that is likely a function of how the pandemic is spreading among those who gets tests. It is becoming clearer that the pandemic can be split into that for those who can afford to isolate and those who cannot (https://www.theguardian.com/society/2021/jan/16/low-paid-shun-covid-tests-cost-of-self-isolating-too-high). If the pandemic is actually still continuing at early Jan/late Dec levels among those less likely to get tests, then I fear for a jump back up.

3466853 reported on WHO dashboard 21/1/21 which will proably not include 21st numbers as not yet released. Eleven days to go seven day average c42k but coming down with last few days sall <40k. This puts <4m very likely now.
https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb

Numbers continue to fall, if the question includes cases reported to WHO on the 1 Feb then there would need to be 44.5k cases per day to reach 4M. Numbers have been well below that for quite a while now. This question should really state a cut-off time on the 1st Feb as the position at the start and end of the day could make all the difference.

Clear correlation between low number of PCR tests and low number of cases in past few days. Testing has been increasing in today's report, and is well below capacity, so it may continue to increase until month's end. As positivity rate is and could remain about close to 10%, the daily rate of cases could rise again as well, as the situation in the UK will still not be entirely under control. It'll finally be very close, but I'm willing to make a bet.

7 day average is now down to 42,000. Cases would need to go back above 45,000 a day to top 4,000,000. Clear downward trajectory in cases over the last 2 weeks. 5% contingency for possible data revision.
Data continue to confirm that the UK is on track to finish the month at around 3.9M cumulative cases. (barring a data revision)
The UK would have to average less than 47k per day over the next 12 days to fall under 4 million. Currently at 43.4k cases and falling. This is looking pretty likely.
With WHO numbers it´s 43567 per day to stay in bin 3. 7-day moving average at 43256, trend clearly down (worldometers numbers). I´ve been too pessimistic so far...
https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb
Cases are trending down since Jan 10, and they would have to average more than 47,000 cases/day to reach 4000000.
Significant drop in case numbers in the last 4 days. Unless it goes back up to 44,428+ cases a day, it will no longer reach 4,000,000, which is great for the UK, but bad for my Brier.

New case numbers are falling to below 40k a day, suggesting the lockdown is having its intended effect. The lockdown will almost certainly not be eased in the next week, suggesting current numbers will either stabilise (around 40k a day, pre Christmas levels) or fall further to around 20k a day (numbers following the second lockdown). In a stabilisation scenario we may just reach slightly over the 4m mark, which is why the suggested 15% likelihood.

The additional factor to add into this mix is the recent set of lockdowns for the UK that has been extended through March. This lockdown started January 5th and the UK saw an 80K decrease in cases. This trend is expected to continue given the restrictions that are in place. https://www.bbc.com/news/explainers-52530518

The most recent 5-day cases average has dropped to about 46,381 per day. With 14 days left in the question maintaining (or increasing) this average would still result in more than 4 million cases total on 2/1/21. (https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb)

37,535 reported today. Risks of revisions due to increased testing pressure remain. Previous examples are 11,000 cases (https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-55105307) and 16,000 cases (https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-54412581). This is likely to be tight under 4,000,000, I'm expecting just under 3.9million at roughly 35,000 daily cases without revisions.

as of 17/1/21 there are 3,395,959 with seven day daily average now down to c50,000 and dropping. 14 days to go ie to include 31/1/21 reported 1/2/21 would give just over 4m. therefore the rate of drop in the daily average is now key. Actual number on 17/1 was 38k significantly below the seven day average. This suggests <4m now.

Well a lot has changed in a week! Now looking likely that sub 4 million will be the outcome. I think my previous prediction gave too much likelihood to over 4 million for this forecast because on the current 7 day average it would still breach 4 million, although of course case numbers should drop below current average.
Today: 3,357,000 Since my last forecast, daily new cases: 41,000 to 55,000

38,598 cases today. It has been a sharp decline, one that should be enough to put the number of cases below 4,000,000. I expect the decline to slow, but crucially it should be below 40,000 per day. However the final result is going to be very close.

Adjusting my initial forecast down slightly due to lower rates in the last week. If the current rates holds (daily average since 1/11) there should be about 4.26M cases; ranging from 75% to 110% gives a shade over 4M to 4.372M.
Cases/day trending up

Annoyed at myself for being overly certain on previous forecasts. Now looks like a clear downward trend in all regions. 46,000 cases per day is the rate for 4 million which is roughly what the rate has been at for the last few days. If it goes down at all, we'll go below. If it goes up at all, we'll go above. It looks to me like additional mixing around Christmas undermined the impact of tier 4 and now without Christmas mixing and with national lockdown the R number has gone below 1. I think given ongoing lockdown cases are more likely to continue to drop or level off than rise, but anything could happen.

I feel like I am trying to play an awful game of signal vs noise. The trend seems down. 16 days out and we have a daily cases number below the required number for 4,000,000. Even if that is natural variaton, one would expect the average figure to reduce over the next 16 days.
seven day average slowing towards 50k per day and less. that puts <4m much more likely
Still think the avg won’t be <46k , can’t see how.

The most recent 7-day cases average is about 52,977/day, but the recent 5-day average is lower, at 48,570 cases/day (1/11-1/15/21). 17 days left in the question multiplied by the lower 5-day average = about 825,686 new cases possible by 2/1/21. That would still lead to about 4,085,948 total cases by 2/1. (3,260,262 current cases + 825,686 projected average.) (https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb)

Would have to average under 46.3k cases per day to drop below 4 million. Currently averaging 53.1k cases per day and dropping. Remains to be seen if the sudden drop maintains or was a temporary downward spike, and how quickly the downward trend continues.

As of the 15th Feb: 3.2m and 47.5k a day. It is likely given the stay at home measures that there will be a drop of announced cases (so do not believe rate of covid cases will increase beyond 47.5k/day) - but will not drop enough to be less than 350k
Another update. The government update seems to have gone up by ~6,000 daily cases in an hour.

48,682 cases reported today. The window is closing on the reduction in cases trend and similar effects have been seen before where a short drop in cases is followed by a contined rise (thanks to @SE_Meyer for spotting that). Nonetheless, some form of peak appears to have been met. The next few days will be critical to deciding the outcome (sorry for sounding like a sports commentator). I have reduced the probability of below 4,000,000 to reflect the lack of movement down in cases.
I'm just eyeballing graphs here. Cases will continue to fall, but I don't know by how much. Cumulative cases will continue to rise, but will they top 4 million? Probably not, but maybe

A small change to reflect the persistent rise at 48,000. But I still think numbers should come down. The 13% represents the odds of a spike appearing for some reason. That spike would originate from behaviour over the next week, so from then the probability of over 4,000,000 can come down. There is also a small chance of cases levelling off at around 45,000 per day, however that is unlikely in such a large scale system. Case rates will (most probably) either be falling or rising, even if very slowly.

It seems I was too optimistic with my last forecast, and the covid cases per day are rising again even with Johnson's lockdown restrictions. Also, the new variant is likely outcompeting the original, so a larger proportion of infected will have the more transmissible variant. The vaccine will not have an impact until after the question has closed (https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-55612270).
The 1/13 total (as posted on 1/14 is 3,164,055. Assuming 18 days (reports) remaining until the question is final and that the last two days of totals are not complete.
At the current rate, trajectory heading to 4,000,000...rather tricky
Adjusting projected 2/1/21 total downward for now + watching if recent decline in cases continues. https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb

I've been all over the place on this question, but all the indicators for new cases are now pointing in the right direction. The main other consideration I have is the rollout of asymptomatic testing, but this could in theory help bring cases down towards the end of the the month.
Lockdown means cases have peaked estimate 30000 a day average for next 18 days roughly 600000. Certainly enough to exceed 3.5 mil but not enough to go over 4.

3m exceeded. 18 days to go. Bin 3 - need about 27k cases per day Bin 4 - need about 54k cases per day Bin 5 - need about 81k cases per day Current cases about 45k per day. This gives bin 3. Lockdown in place for a couple of weeks though (not sure how much people are observing though) which should mean cases tail off a bit making the threshold for bin 4 hard to reach. Weighing more to bin 3.

This is a battle between the UK’s lockdown efforts and the new, more contagious strain. I’m inclined to give a bit more weight to the lockdown efforts. The count will exceed 4 million if the average daily cases between now and Feb 1 are above 46,441. It’s statistically improbable it will be below 3.5 million or above 4.5 million
Going to be tight around that 4m mark.
Introduction of stricter measures in Scotland, and a third consecutive day under 50,000, this time with less impact of weekend reporting.
Much as cases rose higher than initially projected, cases are now again falling faster than projected.
Rough estimate based on figures today, change over the last 2-3 weeks, and expecting the next 2-3 weeks to be similar as rate of increase decreases.
seven day average still c57k. 3,118,512 reported by WHO as at 12th Jan incl. 19 days to go equals 4.2m.

3. How many confirmed cases of COVID-19 will have been reported by the World Health Organization (WHO) for the United Kingdom as of 1 February 2021? a. Initial Assessment: As of Jan 12, 2021, there have been 3,188,522 confirmed cases in the UK. The number of new cases per day has been on the downslope since Jan 9, possibly because of Boris Johnson’s lockdown(https://covid19.who.int/table, https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/04/british-prime-boris-johnson-imposes-national-lockdown-for-england-to-combat-new-covid-variant.html ), and is currently at 46,169, down from 68,053 3 days earlier. This is an average decrease of 7,294.6 cases per day. This will likely not keep up, but the lockdown will remain in effect until Feb 1, and police are getting tougher on violators (https://www.cnbc.com/2021/01/04/british-prime-boris-johnson-imposes-national-lockdown-for-england-to-combat-new-covid-variant.html, https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-health-coronavirus-britain/uk-police-to-get-tougher-on-covid-lockdown-rulebreakers-idUSKBN29H0OL ), so there’s no reason to expect cases/day to increase in that time frame, and they may even decrease to base levels of around 16,000, as they were before New Year’s. This would likely take around 4 days at the current rate of decline, however, assuming the rate slows and flatlines around 40,000 with 20 days left (worst case scenario):
Based on current trends and the time remaining, but will update depending on this week's data to see if it is likely to go over 4M.
Adjusting due to drop in the rate of new cases in the UK (https://covid19.who.int/table).
second day of under 50,000 cases. Lockdown seems to be truncating cases.
Most likely is the middle band here

Numbers do now seem to be leveling off at around 60,000. This trend would put us in the middle of the 4-4.5M interval and so is relatively robust to modest changes up and down in the rate. However, the leveling off could just be a blip and the overall figures are an amalgamation of many different trends in different regions and driven by different strains of the virus, so I don't think we can entirely write off some more unpredictable dynamics here, hence not heading beyond 95+% just yet.
today: 3,072,353 the 14 last day: 50,000 to 68,000 cases per day
Looks like we have reached the peak in daily cases with current lockdowns. That means the likelihood of bin 5 has decreased. Need to move some weightage away from bin5 to lower bins.

Hope I'm not making too swift a judgement but cases seem to be peaking now and the 7 day average has never been enough to take it over 4.5 million so revising down. Crowd seems to be very certain on 4-4.5m and current average would have it at that level but it wouldn't take that big a fall (or that big a rise!) to take it out of that window, I'm not so sure yet that this will be the outcome as a result but it is definitely the most likely outcome. If we are at peak number of cases the drop off can usually be quite big and it would only need to drop to late December levels by the end of the week to start making sub 4m possible.

Forecasting 4.250M exactly in the middle of this bin. Strict lockdown, desperate NHS and public aware of risks - figures will start to slowly decline over next few days, then more quickly towards end on month.
Averaging a little under 60,000 cases per day for the past seven days. (Avg. = 59,653 from Jan. 5 through Jan. 11.) (https://covid19.who.int/region/euro/country/gb)
A slight rise in the below 4,000,000 because a daily recorded cases is below 50,000. I think the peak has been reached and the cases will start dropping soon, but don't want to go further today.
Continuing uptrend until 3rd week of January, then hopefully trend of infections will reduce as the lockdowns start to show effects.
R number & infections dropping in London & the SE
There are around 50k new cases a day. In 10 days, 500k new cases and in roughly 20 day, 1 million new cases. The trend is downwards with the strict lockdowns in place.

I was off by a day it appears, so as of today, this needs an average of 44,073.9 cases per day to resolve at 4,000,000+, and 69,073.9 cases per day to resolve at 4,500,000+. There are too many cases on average per day for it to be below 4,000,000, and the number to keep it in bin 3 decreases every day. Today it is between 19,073.9 and 44,073.9 to stay in bin 3.

The UK currently has over 3M cases of COVID-19. Last week alone, cases soared to over 417K new cases reported in that week alone. Given the exponential trajectory of this disease, the winter months, limited quantities of vaccine, and spikes after the holidays, this upward trend will continue.

21 days remaining, to stay under 4,500,000 they would have to average 70.6k cases per day. Currently at about 60k and potentially looks like they could be leveling off. To get below 4,000,000 they would have to average below 46.7k cases per day. This seems pretty unlikely at this point, they could still climb higher, and if they do start dropping usually it's a gradual decline. Putting high confidence in 4 to 4.5 million cases.
I am keeping my pessimistic prognosis.
Based on ZOE Covid-19 study data
Based on today's datapoint

Adjusting my calculations in a more pessimistic direction. Started using a 60,000 baseline rather than 50,000 and have made the R>1 and R=1 scenarios more likely. This is based on reviewing some other well thought out forecasts on here and the message from leading scientists that the current lockdown may well not be enough to turn the tide given the new variant.

With 70000/day until Feb 1, 2950000 + 22 x 70000 = 4497000. If daily infection number will increase further, which is possible due to mutation (here an impressive annimated gif where you can see how it is spreading https://twitter.com/theosanderson/status/1347683706165747714), it will be > 4500k
UK has no control over the case counts right now. The vaccine rollout is having very little impact. My initial enthusiasm about the vaccines is fading and I am being more and more pessimistic.

Flipping again. I think it is going to be close to 4,500,000, but if it doesn't go up soon, it will be hard to get there. As of today, there needs to be at least 46,582.238 cases a day to get over 4,000,000, and 70,391.762 cases per day to get to 4,500,000.
Adjusting again. I think it will still go up
Flipping because of a few slower days than expected.

As of today (9th January) the WHO is reporting there to have been 2,889,423 cases in the UK and 343,784 weekly cases or 49112 daily cases (https://worldhealthorg.shinyapps.io/covid/). The new lockdown and the end of the festive period are likely to reduce the R rate but as the new variant is spreading 50-70% faster and the current lockdown is less stringent than in March, it is far from guaranteed that this will reduce the R rate to under 1. The affect of vaccination is unlikely to have a major impact on cases before the 1st February.

The case numbers are settling with 59,937 reported today (09.01.21) whereas there were 57,725 a week ago (02.01.21). Those numbers are high, but would have to be maintained for the UK to hit the 4,000,000 cases. Over 4.5 million seems very unlikely, unless a surge in cases is hidden in the data somewhere.

Cases may have not levelled off yet, but they seem unlikely to reach the heights required to get to 4.5 cases. I will update the relative probabilities of the bins between 3.5 and 4.5 million. I think the UK will end up close to 4 million, making this difficult.

The evidence that tier 4 (which is roughly equivalent to the national lockdown) has been working to halt the growth in Kent is essentially zero. This gives me no reasons for optimism that the current national lockdown will be sufficient, indeed there are no obvious signs that case growth is particularly slowing. It seems that a lot fewer people decided to get tested on Christmas day and New Year's, and this may have distorted the data to look temporarily as if it was moving in the right direction.

Difficult time to answer this question, with the recent announcement of Army involvement as well as recent new lockdown. The rate of vaccination is currently 47,000 per day, and is likely to increase with 3 vaccines now available to the UK.

according to https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/uk/ the UK currently (as of 8 Jan) has reported 2,957,472 cases, and appears to have an average daily increase of approximately 50k cases each day. With 23 days remaining in January that would put the UK on a glide path to about 4.1M cases. The vaccine may lower these numbers, hence 20% going to 3.5-4M.... but I expect the same type of increase that has been seen.

The rise has been circa 1 million and 600,000 in the last two months respectively. Despite the virus moving faster than the vaccine. I don't think it will increase by more than 1.4m in 3 weeks with the new lockdown restrictions and the Xmas/NY social gatherings out of the picture. The vaccine, travel restrictions and poor weather should (we hope) keep people indoors.

Putting some boundries on the question if the UK can get the 7 day average down to below 50k by the end of the month this would place the amount near the 4 million mark. a scary number without doubt. restrictions have increased to the level of the lockdown in march which reduces the overall infection rate, compliance is lower than previous lockdowns and the new varient spreads fast. trickey one to place: at a flat rate the number of infections to be below the top figure in each band is: A - 4.8k per day B - 26.5k per day C- 48.3k per day D - 70k per day E - over 70k per day
original calculations based on a peak of around 50 needed drastically updated based on the latest figures. Now based on a peak of 70.

2.8m now. 24 days to go. Running about 60k new cases per day. Lockdown just started so infection rates not likely to drop much in next couple of weeks. 60k per day would give 4.2m, 50k per day 4m. So bin 4 most likely. Might go higher or lower.

Bumping this down a bit just in case my numbers do not pan out, but it looks like there was another increase today with a total of 62,322 cases. This is just short of the 3.096% increase I talked about below, which would have been 62,802 cases.

The most recent 7-day cases average = 57,702. (1/1/21 through 1/7/21.) 57,702 cases (average) times 25 days remaining until 2/1/21 = approx. 1,442, 546 potential new cases by that date. The current reported (1/7/21) total cases number of 2,836,805 + 1,442,546 projected additional ones = (about) 4,279,351 total cases possible by 2/1/21.
Signs of numbers peaking, especially in London & SE. Full lockdown likely to have a significant effect in 1-2 weeks.
Still over 60,000 cases per day so the lower estimates a looking extremely unlikely.

In order for this to resolve at less than 4,000,000 the average new cases per day would have to be 48,846.28 or less (4,000,000-2,778,843=1,221,157/25=48,846.28). Each day that goes by where the case numbers are over 48,846.28 will cause this number to decrease in order to still not go over 4,000,000. It appears that the case numbers are going up rapidly, and even though measures are put into place to slow this down, it will not start working for a few weeks. It is likely that it will get much worse over the next few weeks, or at a minimum get a bit worse. If case numbers are to go above 4,500,000, the case average would have to go up to 68,846.28 per day as of today (4,500,000-2,778,843=1,721,157/25 days=68,846.28). This seems more likely considering the large increase in cases over the last few days. However, this number will increase each day that goes by where the numbers are not at or over 68,846.28, as it will take more and more cases to make up the difference. For example, if tomorrow there is 62,500 new cases, the new daily average needed to get over 4,500,000 would be 69,110.708 (4,500,000-2,778,843-62,500=1,658,657/24 days=69,110.708) With that being said, this will very likely be in Bin 4 at a minimum, and potentially in Bin 5 by the end of the time period. Taking into account the potential exponential increase of spread due to the virulence of the new strain of COVID in the UK, I believe it is more likely that we will see an increase big enough in the next few weeks to reach the daily average needed to get into Bin 5 than we are to see it stay in Bin 4. The curve has just started going up, and lock down measures are unlikely to have any real effect for at least 2-3 weeks from when they are implemented. Continued increases will be seen during this time frame, followed by a leveling off and then reduction in new cases over a period of time probably equal to a few weeks. The next few days will tell the full story, as it will continue to require more and more daily cases to reach 4,500,000 if there are no further increases in the daily cases seen in the UK. Since 30 December (last 7 days according to the WHO numbers), there has been a daily average increase of 6.217% in case numbers. While this number is likely to go down over the next few days since the first few days had a huge increase, daily increases in the last five days are averaging at 3.096%, which if this holds steady would mean that the average daily cases needed to go over 4,500,000 by 1 February would be reached by the 11th. I am going to bet heavy on the last bin and will update accordingly as the next few days as we begin to see if there are continued increases or not.

Current WHO figure are at 2.7M and with 60K infections reported each day at present I am being pessimistic and thinking the worst case at present which would make it a projected 4.2M. If the measures in place are effective I will revise this figure down. We are in a race to bring the R number down but I don't think the measures will be as successful given the new variant and lockdown fatigue. I hope I'm wrong as this is also an indicator of deaths.
Curve is going down. Lockdown and vaccines will work. i hope.
On reading some of the responses here, I agree that the chance of under 3,500,000 should be lowered. I was probably being optimistic due to being one of the poor sods stuck in lockdown here.

50,000 cases a day for 25 days would put the UK at ~3,960,000. The odds of the current lockdown making significant reductions to put average daily new cases at 30,000 seem low. Especially as the UK is still waiting to see the impacts of the lockdown. I'm expecting new cases to slightly reduce. The government seem to see the seriousness of the situation and would probably try even harder to reduce cases if they stayed current levels.
